:"42978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44251"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102128"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with shortness of breath and pleuritic chest pain which started suddenly one hour ago. She is also coughing up small amounts of blood. She reports left calf swelling and tenderness since an international flight one week prior but has otherwise been well recently. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination she is alert and oriented. Her pulse rate is 106/min, blood pressure 120/90 mmHg, temperature 36.7\u00b0C and SpO2 96% on room air. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with no ST changes, although her serum troponins are slightly elevated. A repeat ECG is unchanged. A CT pulmonary angiogram is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alteplase infusion","Inferior vena cava filter insertion","Surgical embolectomy","Commence apixaban","Percutaneous coronary intervention"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has had a pulmonary embolus (PE), as evidenced by her presentation and with the findings of the CT pulmonary angiogram of filling defects in lobar and segmental pulmonary arteries (Image). She is not displaying signs of haemodynamic instability. Therefore, the most appropriate management is anticoagulation - while formerly this was typically using a low molecular weight heparin, this has now been superseded by the oral anticoagulants such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eapixaban\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of haemodynamically unstable PE (suggested by signs of decreased end organ perfusion or hypotension), the most appropriate initial management is unfractionated heparin followed by systemic thrombolytic therapy with an \u003Cstrong\u003Ealteplase infusion\u003C/strong\u003E. If this patient were to haemodynamically deteriorate following anticoagulation, thrombolysis would then be indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical embolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated where thrombolysis is contraindicated or unsuccessful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior vena cava (IVC) filter\u003C/strong\u003E insertion is not indicated in acute PE, and is only considered in cases where anticoagulation is absolutely contraindicated. Although this patient likely has a Deep Venous Thrombosis (DVT) which could result in further pulmonary emboli, anticoagulation would treat a DVT as well as the PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous coronary intervention\u003C/strong\u003E (PCI) is not needed as this clinical picture is not consistent with myocardial infarction, troponins have been shown to be elevated in half of patients with pulmonary embolism. Notably, elevated troponins have been found to be associated with increased risk of adverse outcomes and mortality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-massive PE is managed with anticoagulation, preferably a DOAC."],"references":["Konstantinides SV, Meyer G, Becattini C, Bueno H, Geersing GJ, Harjola VP, et al. 2019 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of acute pulmonary embolism developed in collaboration with the European Respiratory Society (ERS). Eur Heart J. 2020;41(4):543-603. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31504429/","Tran HA, Gibbs H, Merriman E, Curnow JL, Young L, Bennett A, et al. New guidelines from the Thrombosis and Haemostasis Society of Australia and New Zealand for the diagnosis and management of venous thromboembolism. Med J Aust. 2019;210(5):227-235. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30739331/","Kilinc G, Dogan OR, Berk S, Epozturk K, Ozsahin SL, Akkurt I. Significance of serum cardiac troponin I levels in pulmonary embolism. J Thorac Dis. 2012;4(6):588-593. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3506790/","Bajaj A, Saleeb M, Rathor P, Sehgal V, Kabak B, Hosur S. Prognostic value of troponins in acute nonmassive pulmonary embolism: A meta-analysis. Heart Lung. 2015;44(4):327-34. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25976228/#:~:text=Elevated%20troponin%20levels%20were%20significantly,(2)%20%3D%2047%25)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84585"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"180"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"12344"},{"type":"media","id":"12345"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21909"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"12344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/12344"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cdac6f47-f3db-4e62-8965-7db397458e98.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cdac6f47-f3db-4e62-8965-7db397458e98.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":666,"height":585}},{"type":"media","id":"12345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/12345"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b6e87f6b-44b8-40d8-8e28-3abab081f011.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b6e87f6b-44b8-40d8-8e28-3abab081f011.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":649,"height":510}},{"type":"media","id":"21909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21909"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mRo0iDATC4v64yVIb75DK26goqaLKc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mRo0iDATC4v64yVIb75DK26goqaLKc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":666,"height":585}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84585"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05